Use the code chunk below to investigate the data set. Feel free to add additional code chunks.

  1. Find the correlation between a persons annual income and the amount of their mortgage in this data set. What does this value tell you?
income <- mortgage$annual_income
amount<- mortgage$mortgage_amount
cor(income, amount)
[1] 0.8536203
  1. Create a scatterplot with mortgage amount as the explanatory variable and annual income as the response variable. Describe the association.
# Create scatterplot
plot(amount,                    # variable on x-axis
     income,                        # variable on y-axis
     pch = 16,                    # filled-in circles
     cex = 1,                     # larger circle size
    # las = 3,                     # rotate numbers on y-axis
     xlab = "Income",           # x-axis label
     ylab = "Mortgage Amount") # y-axis label
# Avoid scientific notation for numbers
options(scipen = 999)  

# Plot without the x-axis drawn
plot(amount, 
     income, 
     pch = 16, 
     cex = 1, 
     xaxt = "n",                  # suppress default x-axis
     xlab = "Income", 
     ylab = "Mortgage Amount")

# Add a custom x-axis
axis(1, 
     at = seq(100000, 600000, by = 100000), 
     labels = c("100K", "200K", "300K", "400K", "500K", "600K"))

  1. If annual income was converted from dollars to pennies, would the correlation increase, decrease or remain the same?
#df$price_pennies <- df$price_dollars * 100
penn_income <- income * 100
plot(amount, 
     penn_income, 
     pch = 16, 
     cex = 1, 
     xaxt = "n",                  # suppress default x-axis
     xlab = "Income", 
     ylab = "Mortgage Amount")
